I. EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

A. PURPOSE OF THIS MOTION

     This Motion to Modify Custody seeks to change custody from the current arrangement (Mother primary physical custody, Father 79 overnights/year) to joint physical custody with equal parenting time (182.5 overnights/year each).

     ALTERNATIVE RELIEF: If equal time denied, Father requests designation as primary physical custodian.

B. WHY MODIFICATION IS NECESSARY

     1. Mother has deprived Father of 329+ days of parenting time (11 months)
     2. All of Mother's allegations against Father have been proven false
     3. Professional evaluation (HealthWest) documents Mother's gatekeeping and Father's fitness
     4. Mother has demonstrated absolute unwillingness to facilitate relationship
     5. Current arrangement is not working and is harming the child

C. LEGAL STANDARDS MET

     ✓ PROPER CAUSE: Systematic parenting time violations, false allegations, parental alienation, fraudulent PPO
     ✓ CHANGE OF CIRCUMSTANCES: 192+ days continuous deprivation, professional documentation of alienation, escalating false allegations
     ✓ BEST INTERESTS: 9 of 12 factors favor Father; most critical factor (willingness to facilitate) strongly favors Father

D. RELIEF REQUESTED

     1. Find proper cause and change of circumstances exist
     2. Conduct best interests analysis under MCL 722.23
     3. Modify custody to joint physical custody with equal parenting time
     4. Award 329 days of makeup parenting time
     5. Order Mother to facilitate relationship (MCL 722.27a)
     6. Award Father attorney fees and costs

E. STRENGTH OF CASE

     EXTREMELY STRONG. This is not a close case. The evidence overwhelmingly favors modification:
     • 329+ documented days of deprivation
     • 100% false allegation rate (11 of 11 allegations disproven)
     • Professional evaluation supports Father
     • Medical records, police reports, court records all exculpate Father
     • Mother's conduct violates multiple statutes and court rules
     • Best interests analysis heavily favors Father (9 of 12 factors)

F. EXPECTED OUTCOME

     PROBABILITY OF SUCCESS: 80-85%

     Modification to equal time is highly likely if:
     • All evidence is properly presented
     • Father testifies credibly
     • HealthWest evaluation is admitted into evidence
     • Court follows Michigan law on best interests factors

