III. LEGAL BASIS AND STRATEGY

A. LEGAL STANDARDS

     1. ESTABLISHED CUSTODIAL ENVIRONMENT (MCL 722.27(1)(c))

          Standard: "The child naturally looks to the custodian in that environment for guidance, discipline, the necessities of life, and parental comfort." Foskett v Foskett, 247 Mich App 1 (2001).

          Application: Established custodial environment exists with BOTH parents.
          • Father exercised 50% time for 5 years (2019-2024)
          • Child looked to Father for all parenting functions
          • Mother has been primary since July 17, 2024

          Burden: If ECE with both parents: Preponderance of evidence
                  If ECE with Mother only: Clear and convincing evidence

          Father's Position: ECE exists with both parents. Even if only with Mother, Father can meet clear and convincing standard.

     2. PROPER CAUSE (MCL 722.27(1)(c))

          Standard: "One or more appropriate grounds that have or could have a significant effect on the child's life to the extent that a reevaluation of the child's custodial situation should be undertaken." Shade v Wright, 291 Mich App 17 (2010).

          Burden: Clear and convincing evidence

          Father's Proof:
          ✓ 329+ days parenting time violations (Friend v Friend, 407 Mich 968 (1979))
          ✓ Pattern of false allegations (Berger v Berger, 277 Mich App 700 (2008))
          ✓ Parental alienation (Pierron v Pierron, 282 Mich App 222 (2009))
          ✓ Fraudulent PPO (Dailey v Kloenhamer, 291 Mich App 660 (2011))
          ✓ Material changes since July 17, 2024 order

          Conclusion: Proper cause established.

     3. CHANGE OF CIRCUMSTANCES (MCL 722.27(1)(c))

          Standard: "Circumstances that have changed since the entry of the last custody order and that have or could have a significant effect on the child requiring a reevaluation." Shade v Wright, 291 Mich App 17 (2010).

          Burden: Clear and convincing evidence

          Father's Proof:
          ✓ 192+ days continuous deprivation (since 8/8/25)
          ✓ HealthWest evaluation completed (professional documentation)
          ✓ Escalating false allegations post-order
          ✓ Mother's demonstrated unwillingness to facilitate

          Timeframe: Since July 17, 2024 order (19 months ago)

          Conclusion: Change of circumstances established.

     4. BEST INTERESTS (MCL 722.23)

          Standard: Twelve statutory factors; Court must address all factors

          Burden: Clear and convincing evidence (if ECE with Mother only)
                  Preponderance of evidence (if ECE with both)

          Father's Analysis:
          • Factor (a): Favors Father or Equal
          • Factor (b): Favors Father
          • Factor (c): Equal
          • Factor (d): Favors Mother (but compromised by unlawful means)
          • Factor (e): Equal
          • Factor (f): STRONGLY Favors Father (moral fitness)
          • Factor (g): STRONGLY Favors Father (HealthWest cleared Father)
          • Factor (h): Equal
          • Factor (i): N/A (child age 5)
          • Factor (j): EXTREMELY STRONGLY Favors Father (willingness to facilitate)
          • Factor (k): Favors Father (no domestic violence; false allegations)
          • Factor (l): Favors Father (professional recommendation, MCL 722.27a, child's needs)

          SCORE: Father 9, Mother 1, Equal 2

          Conclusion: Best interests overwhelmingly favor modification.

     5. PARENTING TIME PRESUMPTION (MCL 722.27a)

          Standard: "A child has a right to parenting time with a parent unless the court determines by clear and convincing evidence that parenting time, even with conditions, would endanger the child's physical, mental, or emotional health." MCL 722.27a(1).

          Burden: On party opposing parenting time (Mother) to prove endangerment by clear and convincing evidence

          Application:
          • No clear and convincing evidence of endangerment exists
          • All allegations disproven
          • HealthWest found no concerns
          • Presumption favors maximum parenting time for Father

          Conclusion: Father entitled to substantial parenting time under statutory presumption.

B. LITIGATION STRATEGY

     1. EMPHASIZE THE 329+ DAYS DEPRIVATION

          This is the most powerful fact. Eleven months of deprivation is extreme, unconscionable, and demands immediate remedy.

     2. EMPHASIZE 100% FALSE ALLEGATION RATE

          Every single allegation has been disproven. This demonstrates Mother's pattern of dishonesty and manipulation.

     3. RELY HEAVILY ON HEALTHWEST EVALUATION

          The HealthWest evaluation is professional, independent, comprehensive, and completely supports Father. This is the "silver bullet" evidence.

     4. FACTOR (j) IS DISPOSITIVE

          Willingness to facilitate relationship is the most critical factor. Mother has demonstrated absolute unwillingness (329+ days). This factor alone justifies modification.

     5. MORAL FITNESS MATTERS

          Mother's pattern of false allegations, fraudulent PPO, and systematic violations demonstrates lack of moral fitness. This is a best interests factor that strongly favors Father.

     6. FOCUS ON CHILD'S NEEDS

          Frame everything in terms of Lincoln's needs:
          • Lincoln needs his father
          • Lincoln has been deprived of his father for 11 months
          • Lincoln's right to both parents has been violated
          • Lincoln's best interests require restoration of relationship

     7. REQUEST EQUAL TIME, NOT PRIMARY CUSTODY (INITIALLY)

          Requesting equal time is more palatable to courts than requesting flip to Father primary. Frame it as "restoring the arrangement that worked" (2019-2024 50/50 arrangement).

          Primary custody to Father is alternative relief if Court declines equal time.

