V. BEST INTERESTS FACTORS ANALYSIS

FACTOR-BY-FACTOR BREAKDOWN (MCL 722.23)

FACTOR (a): Love, Affection, and Emotional Ties

     FINDING: Favors Father or Equal

     EVIDENCE:
     • Father has maintained loving relationship since birth (5 years)
     • Father exercised 50% time for 5 years, demonstrating strong bond
     • HealthWest documents positive father-child bond
     • 329+ days deprivation has damaged but not destroyed bond
     • Child needs both parents' love

     ARGUMENT: Both parents love child, but Father's bond has been maintained despite Mother's interference.

FACTOR (b): Capacity to Provide Love, Affection, and Guidance

     FINDING: Favors Father

     EVIDENCE:
     • HealthWest confirms Father's appropriate parenting capacity
     • Father provided appropriate guidance and care for 5 years
     • Mother's capacity compromised by:
       - Pattern of false allegations (poor judgment)
       - Willingness to use child as weapon
       - Documented alienation behaviors
       - Prioritizing conflict over child's needs

     ARGUMENT: Father has capacity; Mother's capacity is questionable given her conduct.

FACTOR (c): Capacity to Provide Material Needs

     FINDING: Equal

     EVIDENCE:
     • Both parents maintain stable employment
     • Both maintain appropriate housing
     • Both can provide food, clothing, medical care

     ARGUMENT: No advantage to either party on this factor.

FACTOR (d): Stable Environment and Continuity

     FINDING: Favors Mother (but compromised)

     EVIDENCE:
     • Mother has been primary residence since 7/17/24
     • However, child maintained stability in both homes for 5 years before that
     • Current "stability" achieved through unlawful deprivation
     • True stability includes relational stability with both parents

     ARGUMENT: Physical stability favors Mother, but relational stability favors restoration of Father's time. Stability achieved through wrongful means should not be rewarded.

FACTOR (e): Permanence as Family Unit

     FINDING: Equal

     EVIDENCE:
     • Both parents maintain stable homes and employment
     • Both can provide permanence

     ARGUMENT: No advantage to either party.

FACTOR (f): Moral Fitness

     FINDING: STRONGLY Favors Father

     EVIDENCE FOR FATHER:
     • No criminal record
     • No history of dishonesty
     • Complied with all court orders
     • All allegations against him disproven
     • HealthWest found no concerns

     EVIDENCE AGAINST MOTHER:
     • 11 false allegations to law enforcement and courts
     • Fraudulent PPO obtained through misrepresentation
     • 329+ days of parenting time violations
     • Documented parental alienation
     • Abuse of ex parte procedures (5 orders based on false emergencies)
     • Violation of MCL 722.27a
     • Pattern of perjury and dishonesty spanning 2 years

     ARGUMENT: Mother's systematic dishonesty and willingness to lie under oath demonstrates lack of moral fitness. This is a critical factor.

FACTOR (g): Mental and Physical Health

     FINDING: STRONGLY Favors Father

     EVIDENCE FOR FATHER:
     • HealthWest: No mental health issues, instability, or concerns
     • Medical records: No mental health diagnosis
     • Police welfare checks: Father stable and appropriate
     • Court's 7/17/24 order: Awarded equal legal custody (implicit finding of mental fitness)

     EVIDENCE AGAINST MOTHER:
     • No formal diagnosis
     • However, pattern of false allegations and alienation raises questions about judgment and emotional regulation

     ARGUMENT: All allegations of Father's mental instability disproven. Factor strongly favors Father.

FACTOR (h): Home, School, and Community Record

     FINDING: Equal

     EVIDENCE:
     • Child is 5 years old (preschool age)
     • Both parents maintain appropriate homes
     • Both involved in community
     • Father involved in child's activities when permitted time

     ARGUMENT: No significant advantage to either party.

FACTOR (i): Reasonable Preference of Child

     FINDING: Not Applicable

     EVIDENCE:
     • Child is 5 years old - not of sufficient age to express meaningful preference
     • Any expressed reluctance is result of Mother's alienation, not "reasonable preference"

     ARGUMENT: This factor should not be considered due to child's age.

FACTOR (j): Willingness to Facilitate Relationship

     FINDING: EXTREMELY STRONGLY Favors Father

     THIS IS THE MOST CRITICAL FACTOR.

     EVIDENCE FOR FATHER:
     • Consistently sought to maintain relationship with child
     • Complied with all court orders
     • Never interfered with Mother's parenting time
     • Never made false allegations against Mother
     • Never sought to eliminate Mother from child's life
     • Completed HealthWest evaluation as requested
     • Demonstrated willingness to co-parent

     EVIDENCE AGAINST MOTHER:
     • 329+ days of wrongful deprivation
     • Systematic false allegations designed to eliminate Father
     • Fraudulent PPO obtained to interfere with parenting time
     • Abuse of ex parte procedures (5 suspension orders)
     • Documented parental alienation (per HealthWest)
     • Violation of MCL 722.27a presumption
     • Complete unwillingness to facilitate any relationship
     • Active campaign to destroy father-child relationship

     CASE LAW: Michigan courts recognize that willingness to facilitate is one of the most important factors. Foskett v Foskett, 247 Mich App 1 (2001); Simons v Gisvold, 236 Mich App 163 (1999).

     ARGUMENT: Mother has not merely failed to facilitate—she has actively and systematically destroyed the relationship. This factor alone justifies modification.

FACTOR (k): Domestic Violence

     FINDING: Favors Father

     EVIDENCE:
     • No domestic violence occurred
     • All allegations of threat, assault, danger disproven by:
       - Police investigations (no charges)
       - Medical records (no injuries)
       - HealthWest (no concerns)
       - Court's 7/17/24 order (equal legal custody awarded)
     • Fraudulent PPO obtained through misrepresentation

     ARGUMENT: No domestic violence. False allegations of DV constitute abuse of process. Favors Father.

FACTOR (l): Any Other Relevant Factor

     FINDING: Favors Father

     EVIDENCE:
     • HealthWest recommendation: Restore and expand Father's parenting time
     • MCL 722.27a: Statutory presumption favoring parenting time
     • Contempt: Mother's 329+ days violations = contempt of court
     • Fraud on court: Mother's false allegations constitute fraud (MCR 2.612)
     • Child's developmental needs: 5-year-old needs both parents; father involvement critical
     • Harm from continued deprivation: Each additional day causes further damage

     ARGUMENT: Multiple additional factors favor Father and support modification.

