          ☐ Bring valid photo ID
          ☐ Sign affidavit in front of notary
          ☐ Notary completes jurat and affixes seal

     ☐ 4. Make copies:
          ☐ Original set (for Court filing)
          ☐ Copy set #1 (for Mother/her attorney - service copy)
          ☐ Copy set #2 (for Father's records)
          ☐ Total: 3 complete sets of all documents

     ☐ 5. Obtain filing fee or fee waiver:
          ☐ Contact Court clerk for current filing fee amount
          ☐ Bring cashier's check, money order, or cash (check if Court accepts credit cards)
          ☐ If unable to pay, file Application for Fee Waiver (form available from Court)

B. FILING PROCEDURE

     STEP 1: Serve Mother/Her Attorney (FIRST)

          • Service must occur BEFORE filing (or simultaneously)
          • Serve complete copy of all documents (except Certificate of Service - complete after serving)
          • Methods of service:
            - Personal service (by process server or sheriff) - RECOMMENDED
            - First-class mail (add 3 days to notice period)
            - Email (only if consented to)
          • If Mother has attorney: Serve attorney, not Mother directly
          • Obtain proof of service (process server's affidavit or mail receipt)

     STEP 2: Complete Certificate of Service

          • Fill in method of service used
          • Fill in date and time of service
          • Sign under penalty of perjury

     STEP 3: File with Court

          • Go to: 14th Judicial Circuit Court, Family Division
                   990 Terrace Street
                   Muskegon, MI 49442
          • File during business hours: Monday-Friday, 8:00 AM - 5:00 PM
          • Bring:
            - Original Motion, Brief, Affidavit (notarized), Proposed Order, Schedule
            - Certificate of Service (completed)
            - All exhibits with index
            - Proof of service on Mother
            - Filing fee or approved fee waiver
          • Clerk will:
            - File stamp all documents
            - Assign hearing date (or instruct you to notice hearing)
            - Return conformed copies to you

     STEP 4: Notice of Hearing

          • If Court sets hearing date at time of filing:
            - Note date, time, courtroom on calendar
            - Serve Notice of Hearing on Mother/her attorney
          • If Court requires you to notice hearing:
            - Contact judicial secretary to obtain available dates
            - Prepare Notice of Hearing
            - Serve on Mother/her attorney at least 21 days before hearing
            - File proof of service of Notice of Hearing

C. TIMING REQUIREMENTS (MCR 3.211)

     • Motion must be served at least 21 DAYS before hearing (unless Court shortens time)
     • If service by mail, add 3 days (total 24 days)
     • Count calendar days, not business days
     • Exclude day of service; include day of hearing

     EXAMPLE:
     • Hearing date: March 15, 2026
     • Service deadline: February 22, 2026 (21 days before)
     • If service by mail: February 19, 2026 (24 days before)

D. EXPEDITED/EMERGENCY HEARING

     If seeking expedited hearing (less than 21 days notice):

     • Must show "good cause" for shortening notice period
     • File separate motion: "Motion for Expedited Hearing on Motion to Modify Custody"
     • Explain why expedited hearing necessary (e.g., ongoing harm to child from deprivation)
     • Court has discretion to grant or deny
     • Even if granted, must still provide reasonable notice to Mother

E. AFTER FILING

     ☐ Calendar hearing date immediately
     ☐ Prepare for hearing (see Section IX)
     ☐ Gather additional evidence if needed
     ☐ Subpoena witnesses (including HealthWest evaluator) at least 10 days before hearing
     ☐ Prepare direct examination questions for self and witnesses
     ☐ Prepare cross-examination questions for Mother
     ☐ Review Rules of Evidence
     ☐ Prepare trial notebook/binder with exhibits and notes

