VII. SERVICE REQUIREMENTS

A. WHO MUST BE SERVED

     • Emily A. Watson (Defendant/Mother), OR
     • Mother's attorney of record (if represented)

B. WHAT MUST BE SERVED

     • Motion to Modify Custody
     • Brief in Support
     • Affidavit (notarized)
     • Proposed Order
     • Proposed Parenting Time Schedule
     • All exhibits
     • Notice of Hearing (if date set)

     (Certificate of Service is filed with Court, not served on Mother)

C. METHODS OF SERVICE (MCR 2.107)

     1. PERSONAL SERVICE (RECOMMENDED)

          • Hire process server or use sheriff
          • Hand-deliver documents to Mother (or her attorney)
          • Process server completes Affidavit of Service
          • Most reliable method; avoids disputes about whether service occurred

     2. MAIL SERVICE

          • Send by first-class mail, postage prepaid
          • Must add 3 days to notice period
          • Send to Mother's last known address (or attorney's office)
          • Keep proof of mailing (certified mail receipt recommended but not required)

     3. EMAIL SERVICE (IF CONSENTED)

          • Only if Mother (or her attorney) has consented in writing to email service
          • Send to email address designated in consent
          • Keep proof of email (send receipt)
          • Not generally recommended unless prior consent exists

D. TIMING OF SERVICE

     • Must occur at least 21 days before hearing (24 days if by mail)
     • Serve as soon as possible after filing (or before filing)
     • Do not delay—clock starts ticking when Court sets hearing date

E. PROOF OF SERVICE

     • Must file proof of service with Court before hearing
     • Forms of proof:
       - Affidavit of Service (by process server)
       - Affidavit of Mailing (by person who mailed)
       - Certified mail receipt
       - Email delivery receipt
     • File at least 3 days before hearing

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

VIII. ANTICIPATED TIMELINE

A. FILING TO HEARING: 21-60 DAYS

     Day 1: File Motion and serve Mother
     Days 2-21: Waiting period for Mother to respond
     Day 21+: Hearing held

     LIKELY TIMELINE IN MUSKEGON COUNTY: 30-45 days from filing to hearing (depending on Court's calendar)

B. HEARING TO DECISION: 0-30 DAYS

     • Court may rule from bench (decision immediately after hearing)
     • Or Court may take matter under advisement and issue written opinion later (within 30 days typically)

     LIKELY TIMELINE: Decision within 14 days of hearing

C. TOTAL TIME FROM FILING TO DECISION: 30-90 DAYS

     • Best case: 30 days (expedited hearing, immediate bench ruling)
     • Typical case: 45-60 days
     • Worst case: 90 days (delayed hearing, Court takes time to rule)

D. IMPLEMENTATION OF NEW CUSTODY ORDER

     • Once order entered, effective immediately (unless order specifies otherwise)
     • Equal parenting time schedule begins immediately
     • Makeup time (329 days) scheduled over next 18 months per Father's discretion

E. POTENTIAL DELAYS

     • Mother may file response/counter-motion (extends timeline)
     • Mother may request adjournment (Court may grant delay)
     • Court calendar may be congested (hearing date pushed out)
     • If Court requires additional evidence/evaluation (delays decision)

F. STAY PENDING APPEAL

     • If Court grants modification, Mother may appeal
     • Mother may request stay pending appeal (freeze new order until appeal decided)
     • Father should oppose stay (irreparable harm from continued deprivation)
     • Appellate process adds 6-12 months if Mother appeals

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

IX. HEARING PREPARATION

A. BEFORE THE HEARING

     1. SUBPOENA WITNESSES (at least 10 days before hearing)

          Essential witness: HealthWest evaluator
          • Subpoena evaluator to testify and bring evaluation records
          • Evaluator's testimony is critical to admit HealthWest evaluation
          • Evaluator can explain findings, methodology, conclusions
          • Evaluator can be cross-examined by Mother's attorney

          Optional witnesses:
          • Character witnesses (people who can testify about Father's parenting)
          • Police officers (who investigated allegations)
          • Medical providers (who evaluated Father and found no concerns)
          • Friends/family who witnessed Mother's gatekeeping

     2. PREPARE EXHIBITS

          • Organize all 28 exhibits in binder with tabs
          • Create Exhibit List (Exhibit A, Exhibit B, etc.)
          • Make 4 copies: Judge, Mother's attorney, witness, Father
          • Pre-mark exhibits with stickers
          • Have originals ready for authentication

     3. PREPARE TESTIMONY

          Father's Direct Examination:
          • Relationship with Lincoln (from birth to present)
          • 50/50 arrangement that worked (2019-2024)
          • July 17, 2024 order (reduction to 79 overnights)
          • Mother's false allegations (address each one)
          • 329+ days of deprivation (impact on Father and child)
          • HealthWest evaluation (participation and findings)
          • Fitness as parent (employment, housing, no criminal record, etc.)
          • Willingness to facilitate relationship with Mother
          • Why equal time is in Lincoln's best interests
          • Commitment to makeup time and future co-parenting

          Cross-Examination of Mother:
          • 329+ days deprivation (force her to admit or deny each period)
          • False allegations (confront with evidence disproving each)
          • HealthWest findings (confront with evaluator's conclusions about gatekeeping)
          • Failure to facilitate relationship
          • MCL 722.27a violations
          • Pattern of using court system to eliminate Father

     4. PREPARE LEGAL ARGUMENT

          Opening Statement (2-3 minutes):
          • This case is about 329+ days of wrongful deprivation
          • Mother has systematically made false allegations (100% false rate)
          • Professional evaluation supports Father
          • 9 of 12 best interests factors favor Father
          • Current arrangement is not working and is harming Lincoln
          • Modification to equal time is necessary and appropriate

          Closing Argument (5-10 minutes):
          • Summarize evidence presented
          • Walk through best interests factors
          • Emphasize factor (j) - willingness to facilitate
          • Emphasize moral fitness concerns (factor f)
          • Request equal parenting time
          • Request makeup time
          • Request attorney fees

B. AT THE HEARING

     1. COURTROOM ETIQUETTE

          • Arrive 15-30 minutes early
          • Dress professionally (suit and tie)
          • Bring all exhibits and notes organized in binder
          • Turn off cell phone
          • Stand when Judge enters/exits
          • Address Judge as "Your Honor"
          • Be respectful at all times (even to Mother and her attorney)
          • Do not interrupt
          • Do not argue with Judge
          • Answer questions directly and honestly

     2. ORDER OF PROCEEDINGS

          a. Opening statements (if allowed)
             - Father presents opening first (2-3 minutes)
             - Mother's attorney presents opening
          
          b. Father's case-in-chief
             - Father testifies (direct examination)
             - Mother's attorney cross-examines Father
             - Father's redirect (if needed)
             - Father calls witnesses (HealthWest evaluator, others)
             - Each witness: direct, cross, redirect
             - Father introduces exhibits
             - Father rests

          c. Mother's case
             - Mother testifies (direct and cross)
             - Mother calls witnesses
             - Mother introduces exhibits
             - Mother rests

          d. Rebuttal (if allowed)
             - Father may present rebuttal evidence

          e. Closing arguments
             - Father argues first (5-10 minutes)
             - Mother's attorney argues
             - Father may have brief rebuttal

          f. Court's ruling
             - Judge may rule from bench immediately
             - Or Judge may take matter under advisement

     3. TESTIFYING TIPS

          • Tell the truth (always)
          • Answer the question asked (don't volunteer extra information)
          • If you don't know, say "I don't know"
          • If you don't remember, say "I don't recall"
          • If you don't understand question, ask for clarification
          • Speak clearly and loudly enough for court reporter
          • Look at Judge when answering (not at attorney asking question)
          • Stay calm (even if Mother's attorney is aggressive)
          • Do not argue with Mother's attorney
          • If objection made, stop talking and wait for Judge's ruling

     4. INTRODUCING EXHIBITS

          • Have exhibit ready to show Judge
          • Ask permission to approach witness/Judge
          • Have witness identify document ("Do you recognize this?")
          • Have witness authenticate ("Is this the HealthWest evaluation?")
          • Lay foundation ("How do you know this is the evaluation?")
          • Move for admission ("I move Exhibit 23 into evidence, Your Honor")
          • If objection, respond to objection
          • If admitted, may use exhibit in examination

     5. OBJECTIONS

          Common objections to anticipate:
          • Hearsay (police reports, medical records - respond with business records exception)
          • Lack of foundation (need to authenticate documents)
          • Relevance (show how evidence relates to best interests factors)
          • Calls for speculation (witness cannot speculate about Mother's motives - stick to facts)

C. AFTER THE HEARING

     • If Judge rules from bench: Order prepared by Father or Judge's staff; sign and file
     • If Judge takes under advisement: Wait for written opinion (usually within 30 days)
     • Once order entered: Serve certified copy on Mother
     • Implement new schedule immediately
     • Begin scheduling makeup time

